misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that variables in Java must be named in alphabetical order (a, b, c, d...) to be properly tracked or executed by the computer in a sequential manner.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: Variable names are arbitrary identifiers and do not influence the execution order or memory allocation logic of the Java Virtual Machine. The computer identifies variables by their name or memory address, not by their alphabetical sequence.

misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that the computer can only process one mathematical operation at a time and that every intermediate result must be assigned to its own unique variable before it can be used in the next part of a formula.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: Java supports complex expression nesting and the 'order of operations' (BODMAS/PEMDAS). The entire distance formula can be calculated in a single line without intermediate variables (e.g., Math.sqrt(Math.pow(x2-x1, 2) + Math.pow(y2-y1, 2))).
